1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:12,353
Imagine two judges reading the exact same answer. Same
words, same prompt, same rubric. The only thing that
changes is the name tag above it: Gemini, Claude, GPT-5.5,
or Kimi.

2
00:00:12,353 --> 00:00:20,074
If the score changes, the label did something. That is the
question behind this video: do AI judges play favorites?

3
00:00:20,074 --> 00:00:27,409
We ran a controlled test across four model families, and
the answer was not a simple yes or no.

4
00:00:27,409 --> 00:00:32,813
One judge showed the clearest causal label bias while
barely recognizing its own writing.

5
00:00:32,813 --> 00:00:38,218
One judge recognized itself perfectly but stayed exactly
label-invariant in the paired test.

6
00:00:38,218 --> 00:00:45,939
And the strongest pattern looked less like ego and more
like a benefit-of-the-doubt effect for weaker answers.

7
00:00:45,939 --> 00:00:55,590
This matters because AI systems are increasingly used as
judges. Researchers use model judges to evaluate generated
answers. Product teams use them for regression tests.

8
00:00:55,590 --> 00:01:05,241
Benchmarks use them when human review would be too slow or
too expensive. That can be useful, but only if we
understand the failure modes.

9
00:01:05,241 --> 00:01:15,278
If a judge sees a model name, a provider name, or a
familiar writing style, the score may stop being a pure
measurement of answer quality.

10
00:01:15,278 --> 00:01:19,910
It can become a mixture of quality, label, style, and
prior expectation.

11
00:01:19,910 --> 00:01:28,789
Here was the setup. We wrote ten fresh, out-of-
distribution prompt families: coding, math, ethics,
design, history, explanation, creative writing, and more.

12
00:01:28,789 --> 00:01:36,896
Four model families answered every prompt: Claude Opus
4.7, Gemini 3.1 Pro, GPT-5.5, and Kimi K2.6.

13
00:01:36,896 --> 00:01:44,617
Then the same four families judged the responses with a
five-part rubric: correctness, completeness, clarity,
creativity, and constraint adherence.

14
00:01:44,617 --> 00:01:53,882
The important design choice was separating two questions.
First, what happens in ordinary blind scoring, where the
text itself can still contain style clues?

15
00:01:53,882 --> 00:02:00,444
Second, what happens when we hold the response text fixed
and only change the displayed author label?

16
00:02:00,444 --> 00:02:04,305
The first result is already a warning against easy
headlines.

17
00:02:04,305 --> 00:02:15,114
In the blind baseline, the pooled average self-preference
gap was small and noisy: about plus zero point three eight
points. But the average hid a sharp split.

18
00:02:15,114 --> 00:02:26,695
Claude showed a raw self-gap of plus two point four three.
GPT-5.5 showed plus one point three three. Gemini showed a
smaller plus zero point six three.

19
00:02:26,695 --> 00:02:33,258
Kimi showed minus two point eight seven. So the headline
is not: all AI judges prefer themselves.

20
00:02:33,258 --> 00:02:39,434
The headline is: different judge families behaved
differently, and the average alone can hide the story.

21
00:02:39,434 --> 00:02:51,016
A raw self-gap is useful, but it is not automatically a
causal bias estimate. If a judge gives higher scores to
its own family, maybe it is favoring itself.

22
00:02:51,016 --> 00:03:00,281
Or maybe that family wrote stronger answers on the chosen
prompts. Or maybe the judge rewards a style that happens
to match its own.

23
00:03:00,281 --> 00:03:08,774
Or maybe it infers authorship from phrasing even when no
label is shown. All of those mechanisms can move an
observational score.

24
00:03:08,774 --> 00:03:14,950
That is why we treated the blind baseline as a clue, not
as the final answer.

25
00:03:14,950 --> 00:03:24,215
Kimi is the clearest cautionary tale. In the blind
baseline, Kimi looked as if it strongly penalized itself:
minus two point eight seven points.

26
00:03:24,215 --> 00:03:34,638
But Kimi-authored answers also scored much lower on this
prompt set. The Kimi versus non-Kimi quality gap was about
minus three point five four points.

27
00:03:34,638 --> 00:03:41,587
Once we adjusted for that quality difference, Kimi's
residual moved positive, to plus zero point six six.

28
00:03:41,587 --> 00:03:52,010
So the raw negative self-gap was not good evidence that
Kimi disliked its own name. It mostly reflected a quality
confound in this particular prompt set.

29
00:03:52,010 --> 00:04:02,819
To test label bias more cleanly, we used a label-swap
design. Take the same answer. Show it once under one
displayed author label and once under another.

30
00:04:02,819 --> 00:04:11,312
Then compare scores within that exact response. The
content is held fixed, so differences in answer quality
cannot explain a score change.

31
00:04:11,312 --> 00:04:18,261
This was a reduced paired design, not every possible label
for every response, so it still has limits.

32
00:04:18,261 --> 00:04:25,981
But it asks a much sharper question than the blind
baseline: did the displayed label itself causally move the
score?

33
00:04:25,981 --> 00:04:32,158
This is where the story became sharper. Gemini showed the
clearest causal displayed-self label effect.

34
00:04:32,158 --> 00:04:44,511
In the paired slice, the Gemini self-label effect was
about plus zero point two nine by residual label contrast,
and plus zero point four four by the per-response self
contrast.

35
00:04:44,511 --> 00:04:49,144
Claude showed a smaller positive trend. Kimi was near zero
and noisy.

36
00:04:49,144 --> 00:04:59,567
GPT-5.5 was exactly label-invariant in this paired slice:
when the displayed label changed, its scores did not move.
So label bias was not universal.

37
00:04:59,567 --> 00:05:02,269
It depended strongly on the judge family.

38
00:05:02,269 --> 00:05:12,692
Here is the public label-swap figure from the research
artifact. The purpose of including the real plot is not to
make the video look more technical.

39
00:05:12,692 --> 00:05:24,274
It is to show the shape of the evidence. The Gemini effect
is the clearest positive causal signal. The GPT-5.5 result
is exactly flat in this paired slice.

40
00:05:24,274 --> 00:05:29,292
Claude is smaller and less decisive. Kimi is near zero
with wide uncertainty.

41
00:05:29,292 --> 00:05:36,627
The visual point is the same as the statistical point: one
headline number would erase the differences that matter.

42
00:05:36,627 --> 00:05:45,506
A tempting explanation is that a model favors its own work
because it recognizes its own writing. But recognition and
favoritism came apart.

43
00:05:45,506 --> 00:05:55,157
Gemini identified its own responses as Gemini in only one
out of ten self cases, yet it showed the clearest causal
displayed-self label effect.

44
00:05:55,157 --> 00:06:05,194
GPT-5.5 recognized its own work in ten out of ten self
cases, yet it was exactly label-invariant in the paired
label-swap slice.

45
00:06:05,194 --> 00:06:11,370
So the mechanism cannot simply be: I know this is mine,
therefore I score it higher.

46
00:06:11,370 --> 00:06:17,547
Another detail makes the mechanism more interesting.
Gemini did not only show a displayed-Gemini boost.

47
00:06:17,547 --> 00:06:28,742
It also showed an anti-Kimi displayed-label penalty: about
minus zero point two four five residual points, with all
seven nonzero prompt signs going negative in that
analysis.

48
00:06:28,742 --> 00:06:36,849
That matters because it pushes against a simple vanity
story. A displayed label can act like a prior about
expected quality.

49
00:06:36,849 --> 00:06:45,728
The judge may be applying more charity to one label and
less charity to another, even when the underlying answer
text is identical.

50
00:06:45,728 --> 00:06:56,923
The strongest mechanism pattern was what we called floor-
raising. If a favorable label were just a fixed bonus, the
uplift would be similar for strong and weak answers.

51
00:06:56,923 --> 00:07:06,960
Instead, for judges with nonzero label effects, the self-
label uplift was larger when the baseline score was lower.
Strong answers were already near the ceiling.

52
00:07:06,960 --> 00:07:16,225
Weaker answers had more room for interpretation, and a
favorable label seemed to buy more benefit of the doubt.
That is not exactly ego.

53
00:07:16,225 --> 00:07:19,699
It is more like a charity correction applied unevenly.

54
00:07:19,699 --> 00:07:27,420
It is important to say what this does not prove. It does
not prove that every AI judge favors itself.

55
00:07:27,420 --> 00:07:37,071
It does not prove that models have human-like egos or
motives. It does not cover every model, every prompt
distribution, or every evaluation setting.

56
00:07:37,071 --> 00:07:40,932
The paired label-swap design was reduced rather than
exhaustive.

57
00:07:40,932 --> 00:07:52,899
The useful claim is narrower and more measurable: visible
labels can causally affect some model judges, in model-
specific ways, and those effects can be separated from
answer quality if you

58
00:07:52,899 --> 00:07:54,443
design the experiment carefully.

59
00:07:54,443 --> 00:08:03,708
The practical lesson is not: never use AI judges. The
judges still shared meaningful quality signal. The lesson
is to use them with guardrails.

60
00:08:03,708 --> 00:08:12,587
Hide irrelevant author or model labels when possible. Use
multiple judges rather than one model family alone. Report
per-judge results before pooling.

61
00:08:12,587 --> 00:08:15,675
Separate observational patterns from causal label-swap
audits.

62
00:08:15,675 --> 00:08:23,782
And be suspicious of a single clean headline number until
it has survived heterogeneity checks, quality controls,
and causal stress tests.

63
00:08:23,782 --> 00:08:32,661
So, do AI judges play favorites? Sometimes, but not all in
the same way. In our test, Gemini's displayed label
mattered causally.

64
00:08:32,661 --> 00:08:38,066
GPT-5.5's displayed label did not move scores in the
paired slice.

65
00:08:38,066 --> 00:08:46,558
Kimi's apparent self-penalty was mostly about response
quality on this prompt set, not a causal dislike of its
own name.

66
00:08:46,558 --> 00:08:53,507
And the clearest mechanism looked like floor-raising for
weaker work. That is messier than yes or no.

67
00:08:53,507 --> 00:09:02,000
It is also the kind of answer we need if AI systems are
going to evaluate more of the world's work.
